#Text=2012 Report on Gender Equality and Development suggests Australian women are doing okay
#Text=Thursday , September 26 , 2013
#Text=Tuesday , World Bank released the 2012 World Development Report ( WDR ) on Gender Equality and Development .
#Text=With few specific mentions of Australia , women in the country appear to be doing better than many other countries discussed .
#Text=This includes areas like education , health , life expectancy , and willingness to work part time .
#Text=Participation in the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women
#Text=In 1979 , the United Nations General Assembly adopted the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women ( CEDAW ) .

#Text=Early on , the report credits the Sex Discrimination Act 1984 , inspired by CEDAW , with dealing with inequality issues such as discrimination based on sex , marital status , and pregnancy or potential pregnancy .

#Text=The WDR 2012 team estimates based on World Values Surveys found little change in attitudes for people who agree that university education is more important for boys than girls , with around 8 % of Australians saying yes between 1994 and 1999 , and 5 % saying yes between 2005 and 2007 .
#Text=About 25 % of Australians said men should have more rights to jobs than women between 1994 and 1999 .
#Text=This dropped to 15 % between 2005 and 2007 .
#Text=The report says married Australian women working part-time are amongst a few nationalities who prefer their current working hours , and would not desire to change to a full time position .
#Text=The report contrasts this to Honduras where married women working part-time would like to move to full-time but are unable to do so because of the lack of available employment .
#Text=The report suggests economic well being is not a good predictor of Australian female fertility .
#Text=The top 20 % of female earners have an average of about 1.5 children compared to the bottom 20 % who have an average of 2 children .
#Text=Current Australian Parliamentarian
#Text=Kate Lundy
#Text=is one of several women who was not in office in 1990 Image : David Howe .

#Text=While girls score slightly lower than boys on the Programme for International Student Assessment mathematics test at around 510 to 520 on the mean score , girls outperformed boys in literacy approximately 530 to 500 .
#Text=The report attributes overall patterns of girls outperforming boys at literacy and boys outperforming girls at maths to gender expectations reinforced in textbooks .
#Text=It sites current examples of this in Australia and Hong Kong .

#Text=On the maths test , Australian girls slightly outperformed girls from Estonia , Belgium and Germany , while girls from New Zealand , Macau , the Netherlands , Canada , Japan , Switzerland , Liechtenstein , Finland , South Korea , Hong Kong and Singapore outperformed their Australian counterparts .
#Text=On the literacy test , Australian girls slightly outperformed their Norwegian and Polish counterparts .
#Text=The only countries sampled outperforming Australian girls at literacy were Japan , New Zealand , Canada , Singapore , Hong Kong , Finland and South Korea .
#Text=From 1991 to 2009 , the gross enrolment ratio for Australian females in primary and secondary school declined by 1 % and 2 % respectively .
#Text=For tertiary education , there was a 52 % increase for females .
#Text=The average life expectancy of Australian women went from 80 in 1990 to 84 in 2009 .
#Text=During the same period , male life expectancy grew from 74 years to 79 years .
#Text=Australia 's Parliament
#Text=had 6 % women in 1990 and grew to 25 % women in 2010 .
